    </div>
    <div class="stat-card">
      <div class="stat-value">-${Math.abs(netCash / 1000).toFixed(2)}B</div>
      <div class="stat-label">Net Debt</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ METHODOLOGY ═══ -->
  <h2>Methodology: Two-Stage DCF</h2>
  <p>We use a <strong>two-stage discounted cash flow (DCF)</strong> model to evaluate Constellation Energy. By projecting future cash flows and discounting them to the present, we can assess what the business is fundamentally worth.</p>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">1</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Start with actual Free Cash Flow</h4>
      <p>Constellation Energy generated <strong>$1.29 billion</strong> in free cash flow in FY2025. This marks a massive turnaround from negative FCF in previous years, largely driven by improved operating performance and strategic positioning in the nuclear energy sector.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">2</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Project FCF growth for 5 years (Phase 1)</h4>
      <p>We model FCF growth at <strong>20% per year</strong> for the next 5 years. This aggressive growth assumption is underpinned by the unprecedented surge in data center power demand (AI) and the premium placed on 24/7 carbon-free nuclear baseload power, combined with IRA nuclear production tax credits.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">3</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Calculate terminal value (Phase 2)</h4>
      <p>After Year 5, we assume FCF grows at a more normalized <strong>2.5% perpetuity growth rate</strong>. The Gordon Growth Model captures all remaining future value beyond the high-growth phase, reflecting stable, regulated-like returns for a mature nuclear utility fleet.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">4</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Discount everything to present value</h4>
      <p>Future cash flows are discounted at <strong>8.5%</strong>. This represents our weighted average cost of capital (WACC). It balances the traditional stability of utility cash flows against the execution risks of new capacity agreements and plant restarts.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="method-step">
    <div class="step-num">5</div>
    <div class="step-content">
      <h4>Subtract net debt, divide by shares</h4>
      <p>Enterprise Value minus Net Debt ($5.24B) gives us Equity Value. We divide this by the diluted shares outstanding (314M) to arrive at the final intrinsic value per share.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ THE THREE ASSUMPTIONS ═══ -->
  <h2>The Three Assumptions That Drive Everything</h2>
  <p>Our valuation rests on three core inputs. For full transparency, here is the rationale behind each number.</p>

  <div class="assumption-grid">
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">FCF Growth Rate (Years 1-5)</div>
      <div class="value">20%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        Constellation is uniquely positioned to benefit from the AI data center boom. Tech giants require massive amounts of 24/7 clean power. With fixed nuclear capacity, CEG can sign long-term PPAs at significant premiums (e.g., the Microsoft Three Mile Island deal). This structural tailwind justifies a 20% near-term growth rate.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Discount Rate (WACC)</div>
      <div class="value">8.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        The 10-Year US Treasury yield sits at 4.18%. Utilities traditionally have lower discount rates due to predictable cash flows, but CEG operates competitive (merchant) generation as well. An 8.5% required return appropriately balances the safety of its nuclear fleet with the risks of merchant power markets.
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="assumption-card">
      <div class="label">Terminal Growth Rate</div>
      <div class="value">2.5%</div>
      <div class="rationale">
        In the long run, growth will likely revert to match broad economic expansion and inflation. A 2.5% perpetual growth rate assumes Constellation maintains its pricing power and structural importance in the US energy grid without growing aggressively to infinity.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FCF PROJECTIONS TABLE ═══ -->
  <h2>Projected Free Cash Flows</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Year</th>
          <th>FCF ($M)</th>
          <th>PV Factor</th>
          <th>Present Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Base (FY2025)</td>
          <td>${fcf2025.toLocaleString()}</td>
          <td>—</td>
          <td>—</td>
        </tr>
        {projectedFCF.map(p => (
          <tr>
            <td>Year {p.year} ({2025 + p.year})</td>
            <td>${p.fcf.toLocaleString()}</td>
            <td>{p.pvFactor.toFixed(4)}</td>
            <td>${p.pvFCF.toLocaleString()}</td>
          </tr>
        ))}
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td colspan="3">Sum of Phase 1 PV</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ TERMINAL VALUE ═══ -->
  <h3>Terminal Value</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Year 6 FCF (Year 5 × 1.025)</td>
          <td>${Math.round(fcfYear6).toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Terminal Value (FCF₆ ÷ (8.5% − 2.5%))</td>
          <td>${terminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
        <tr class="row-total">
          <td>PV of Terminal Value</td>
          <td class="highlight-cell">${pvTerminalValue.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ FINAL CALCULATION ═══ -->
  <h3>Final Valuation</h3>
  <div class="table-wrap">
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th style="text-align:left">Component</th>
          <th>Value ($M)</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>PV of Phase 1 Cash Flows</td>
          <td>${pvPhase1.toLocaleString()}</td>
        </tr>
