  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Nuclear Renaissance:</strong> Further government subsidies or massive tech investments could directly fund new nuclear capacity or SMRs (Small Modular Reactors).</li>
    <li><strong>Long-term Contract Premiums:</strong> As baseload clean power becomes scarcer, CEG could lock in PPAs well above market rates for 10-20 years, massively expanding margins beyond our estimates.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Caps:</strong> Unprecedented utility profits from data centers could trigger regulatory intervention, capping PPA rates or taxing merchant generators.</li>
    <li><strong>Execution Risk:</strong> Restarting dormant plants like Three Mile Island is complex, expensive, and subject to delays or cost overruns.</li>
    <li><strong>Alternative Technologies:</strong> Breakthroughs in geothermal, long-duration battery storage, or fusion could eventually reduce the premium placed on fission nuclear baseload.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why does the model show Constellation as highly overvalued?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">DCF models use current fundamentals and reasonable growth assumptions. CEG's stock price has surged entirely on the <em>future narrative</em> of AI power demand. To justify the current market price, FCF needs to grow at 30%+ annually for years, which requires flawless execution and record-high power pricing. Our model uses a more grounded 20% growth rate.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>How does the Three Mile Island restart affect this?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">The Microsoft deal to restart Crane Clean Energy Center (TMI Unit 1) is a perfect example of the premium tech companies will pay for clean baseload power. We factor this demand into our aggressive 20% FCF growth assumption. However, restarting a plant requires significant upfront capital expenditures, which restrains near-term free cash flow.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is 8.5% the right discount rate for a utility?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Constellation is not a traditional regulated utility; it is the largest competitive (merchant) generator in the US. Merchant power inherently carries more risk than regulated transmission and distribution, demanding a higher discount rate than the typical 6-7% used for regulated peers.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

